          "title": "The righteousness claim — not boasting but covenant fidelity",
          "body": "Verses 21-31 contain the psalm's most theologically sensitive claim: 'The LORD has rewarded me according to my righteousness; according to the cleanness of my hands He has recompensed me' (22:21). Read in isolation and without canonical context, this sounds like merit theology — the kind Paul demolishes in Romans 3-4. But three contextual controls prevent that reading. First, verse 20 has just anchored the rescue in divine delight, not human righteousness. Second, the 'righteousness' David claims is *covenant faithfulness* — he kept the LORD's ways (22:22), did not depart from His statutes (22:23), was blameless (*tamim*, 22:24). This is the righteousness of a covenant partner, not the righteousness of one who has earned justification. Third, the canonical David (Psalm 51; 2 Samuel 11-12) is a confessed sinner who knows himself dependent on God's steadfast love. The claim of verses 21-25 is specific: in his relationship to this particular set of enemies and this particular rescue, David maintained covenant integrity. He did not compromise his allegiance to YHWH, did not defect, did not practice the iniquity his enemies represented. The general principle of verses 26-27 follows: God mirrors back to each person the moral orientation they bring. The faithful find God faithful; the blameless find God blameless; the perverted find God astute in frustrating their schemes (22:27). This is not karma — it is the moral logic of covenant encounter."
