          "body": "Verses 32-46 describe David's military achievements with graphic intensity: pursuing enemies until they were consumed (22:38), pulverizing them as dust, stamping them as mire in the streets (22:43), receiving the submission of foreign nations (22:44-46). Read in isolation this sounds like triumphalism. But the grammar refuses that reading. Verses 33-36 are the theological grammar of the warrior section: 'God is my strong fortress; He makes my way clear; He makes my feet like deer's feet; He trains my hands for battle.' The third-person God-subject continues through verse 40: 'You have girded me with strength; You have subdued my foes under me; You have made my enemies turn their backs.' Every act of military success in verses 38-43 is grammatically preceded by God's equipping in verses 33-40. The warrior boasts of nothing except what God has given. This is the theological logic Swindoll calls 'strength-from-outside' — not the self-made hero but the instrument of divine warfare. The inclusion of internal strife ('the contentions of my people,' 22:44) alongside external enemies broadens the deliverance: Absalom, Sheba, and the Philistines are all caught in the same divine resolution."
