          "body": "The psalm's closing movement (22:47-51) is one of the most theologically loaded passages in the Samuel literature. The doxology of verse 47 — 'The LORD lives! Blessed be my Rock! Exalted be God, the Rock of my salvation!' — is a three-part acclamation that confesses divine vitality (*chay*, 'lives'), divine character (*tsur*, 'Rock'), and divine purpose (*yeshuah*, 'salvation'). The warrant for praise (22:48-49) recapitulates the psalm's themes: God executes vengeance, brings peoples under David, rescues from violent men. The universal scope of praise is announced in verse 50: David will give thanks among the nations (*goyim*) and sing praises to His name. Paul quotes this verse directly in Romans 15:9 as evidence that the inclusion of the Gentiles was always embedded in the Davidic covenant. The psalm's final verse (22:51) names the ultimate ground of everything that has been sung: *chesed* — lovingkindness, covenant loyalty — to His *mashiach* and to David's descendants *forever*. The word *mashiach* here exceeds what any historical David could claim. The *chesed* that extends 'forever' to David's 'seed' (*zera*) points to the one Seed in whom all Davidic promise is concentrated (cf. 2 Samuel 7:12-16; Luke 1:32-33; Acts 2:30-31). The psalm that began with David's personal crisis ends with the unilateral covenant of God guaranteeing an eternal anointed King."
